# All core trading concepts.  

exhaustive, actionable, and relevant for crypto/forex/stocks.
  
🧠 1. Price & Quotes

Bid : Highest price a buyer is willing to pay

Ask (Offer) : Lowest price a seller is willing to accept
Mid-price : (Bid + Ask) / 2, often used in analytics
Spread : Ask − Bid (transaction cost for immediate execution)
Last price : Most recent executed trade
Open / Close / High / Low : Standard OHLC used in charts


🏷 2. Orders & Execution

Market order : Execute immediately at best available price
Limit order : Execute only at a specific price or better
Stop order : Trigger a market order when price reaches a level
Stop-limit order : Trigger a limit order at a specified price
Fill or Kill (FOK) : Execute immediately in full or cancel
Immediate or Cancel (IOC) : Execute any part immediately, cancel rest
Good till canceled (GTC) : Limit order stays until executed or canceled
Good till date/time (GTD) : Limit order expires at a set time
Partial fill : Only part of the order is executed
Slippage : Difference between expected price and executed price
Execution price : The actual price at which an order fills


⚡ 3. Costs & Fees

Spread : Implicit cost of buying at ask / selling at bid
Commission / Fee : Exchange charges for each trade
Overnight / Financing fee : For leveraged positions held overnight
Taxes / Regulatory fees : May apply depending on jurisdiction


🏗 4. Risk & Leverage

Leverage / Margin : Borrowed capital to amplify positions
Margin call : Broker asks for more collateral if losses grow
Liquidation : Broker closes your position to prevent negative balance
Initial margin : Required to open a leveraged position
Maintenance margin : Minimum balance to keep the position open
Notional value : Total value of the leveraged position



📈 5. Market Mechanics

Liquidity : How easily an asset can be bought/sold without moving the price
Volatility : Measure of price fluctuations
Order book : List of open buy/sell orders at each price
Depth of market (DOM) : Visualization of order book levels
Market impact : How your order moves the market
Tick size : Minimum price increment
Lot size / Contract size : Minimum tradeable quantity


🔁 6. Trading Types & Strategies

Scalping : Very short-term trades, small profits per trade
Day trading : Buy/sell within a single trading day
Swing trading : Holding trades for days/weeks
Position trading : Long-term holding
Hedging : Reduce exposure to risk using offsetting trades
Arbitrage : Exploiting price differences across markets
CFD : Contract for Difference – trade on price movement without owning asset
Knock-Out / Barrier products : Leveraged product with built-in stop-loss barrier


🔒 7. Risk Metrics & Analysis

PnL (Profit & Loss) : Total gain or loss of a trade
Unrealized / Realized PnL : Open vs closed positions
Drawdown : Maximum loss from peak capital
Sharpe ratio : Risk-adjusted return metric
Value at Risk (VaR) : Estimated maximum loss in normal conditions
Beta : Volatility relative to market index
Alpha : Performance above benchmark


🧩 8. Order Types & Advanced Features (Optional/Pro)

Iceberg orders : Large order split into small visible chunks
Stop-loss order : Close position to limit loss
Take-profit order : Close position to lock profit
Trailing stop : Stop-loss that moves with price
Good till triggered : Like GTC but activated by condition
Bracket orders : Entry + stop-loss + take-profit in one
OCO (One-Cancels-Other) : Two linked orders; execution of one cancels the other


🌐 9. Market Types / Venues

Spot market : Buying/selling actual assets
Futures : Contract to buy/sell at a future date
Options : Right but not obligation to buy/sell
CFD : Price difference contract
Derivatives : Contracts based on underlying asset
Exchanges : Venue for trades (Binance, Coinbase, NYSE)
Decentralized exchanges (DEX) : On-chain trading (Uniswap, PancakeSwap)



🔄 10. Technical Concepts for Traders

Support / Resistance : Price levels where markets reverse
Trend / Uptrend / Downtrend : Direction of price movement
Volatility measures : ATR, Bollinger Bands, etc.
Indicators : RSI, MACD, EMA, SMA
Candlestick patterns : Doji, hammer, engulfing, etc.
Momentum / Mean reversion : Core trading logic


🧠 Bonus: Developer-Specific Concepts 

    Slippage simulation
    Spread modeling
    Order book depth simulation
    Latency & execution simulation
    Concurrency / race conditions for orders
    Backtesting engine
    Position management / portfolio PnL tracking
    Margin & liquidation calculation engine

💡 Senior tip: order book + spread + slippage + margin + liquidation 

# Momentum

Le momentum en trading désigne la force et la vitesse d’un mouvement de prix. Autrement dit, il répond à la question : est-ce que le prix monte (ou descend) rapidement et avec puissance, ou est-ce que le mouvement s’essouffle ?

 Idée simple  
Si un actif monte rapidement et régulièrement → momentum positif  
S’il chute fortement → momentum négatif  
S’il stagne → momentum faible  

 Les traders utilisent le momentum pour suivre la tendance plutôt que la deviner.  

 Exemple concret  
Une action passe de 100€ à 120€ en quelques jours → momentum fort haussier  
Elle monte ensuite lentement de 120€ à 122€ → momentum en perte de vitesse  

 Même si le prix continue de monter, le momentum diminue, ce qui peut signaler un futur retournement.   

 Indicateurs de momentum courants  
Voici les outils les plus utilisés :  
RSI (Relative Strength Index)→ mesure si un actif est suracheté (>70) ou survendu (<30)   
MACD (Moving Average Convergence Divergence)→ montre les changements de momentum via des croisements  
Stochastique→ compare le prix actuel à sa plage récente  

 À quoi ça sert ?  
Le momentum aide à :  
Entrer dans une tendance forte  
Éviter les marchés sans direction  
Repérer les essoufflements de tendance  
Confirmer un signal d’achat ou de vente  

